          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Hungary to leave ICC</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/viktor-orban-benjamin-netanyahu-meeting-budapest.png" alt="Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel in Budapest" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Prime Minister Viktor Orban of Hungary and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel in Budapest. Credits: Janos Kummer/Getty Images</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Hungary has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-04-2025-h1-1-decided-to-withdraw?source=website" target="_blank">decided to withdraw</a> from the International Criminal Court (ICC), becoming the third country after Burundi and the Philippines. The move coincides with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu’s visit to Budapest despite an ICC arrest warrant against him for alleged war crimes in Gaza.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          Gergely Gulyás, chief of staff for PM Viktor Orbán, criticized the ICC for becoming a “political body” and straying from its original purpose. He argued that Hungary never incorporated the Rome Statute into domestic law, rendering ICC warrants unenforceable. Orbán condemned the ICC’s political interference and invited Netanyahu to defy the court.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
